"Why rambling on interviews can be holding you back. \n\nRambling during an interview is a common issue that can affect your progress in the hiring process. The candidates who stand out are able to communicate their experiences and skills in a clear, concise, and engaging way.\n\nEarly in my career, I struggled with this too, whether it was in interviews, presentations, or networking. Itâ€™s easy to ramble when youâ€™re nervous, or trying to fill silence. But over time, I learned a few key strategies that helped me keep my responses focused and impactful.\n\nHere are some tips that helped me:\n\n1. Practice Positive Affirmations\n\nBefore any interview or presentation, take a moment to remind yourself that you deserve this opportunity, that you're knowledgeable, and that you're ready. Positive affirmations help calm your nerves, reduce anxiety, and give you the confidence to express yourself clearly.\n\n2. Slow Down Your Speech\n\nIt may sound counterintuitive, but slowing down your speaking pace can make a huge difference. When you talk too fast, it's easy to stumble over words or add unnecessary filler. Slowing down not only gives you time to think but also helps you sound more thoughtful and deliberate.\n\n3. Record Yourself\n\nRecording yourself can feel awkward, but itâ€™s one of the most effective ways to improve. Listening to your responses will help you identify areas where you can refine your delivery. If listening to yourself feels uncomfortable, try practicing with a friend for feedback.\n\nTry these tips next time you have an interview or a big presentation and remember this will take practice so don't be hard on yourself.\n\nâ€¦more"
