"Data Analysis: It's Not Just About Dashboards\n\nData analysis isnâ€™t just about creating aesthetically pleasing dashboards, itâ€™s about solving real problems. This became clear as we kicked off the Data Analytics course with. By considering a theoretical case of an online retail store with Declining ratings, I got a hands-on walkthrough of the workflow of an analyst in any industry setting. Here are my key takeaways;\n\nUnderstanding Customer Satisfaction in Online Retail Stores\n\nTo analyze customer satisfaction in an online retail store, we need to break down the process into manageable steps.\n\nStep 1: Define the Problem and Business Objective\n\nWe begin by defining the problem we want to solve and identifying our business objective. In this case, the problem is 'Declining Ratings' and our goal is to analyze customer feedback and satisfaction ratings to pinpoint key pain points affecting customer experience and provide actionable recommendations for improvement.\n\nStep 2: Identify Key Questions and Available Data\n\nNext, we determine the specific questions we want to ask and assess what data is available to help answer them e.g what are the major complaints from customers, is customer satisfaction lower in some product categories, are there patterns in negative feedback like late delivery, poor product quality, etc.\n\nStep 3: Gather and Prepare the Data\n\nWe gather relevant data from various sources (customer review datasets, customer log complaints, order delivery data, return/refund data). We extract data using techniques such as:\n\nExtracting structured data using SQL\nCollecting unstructured data through web scraping or API integrations from website. Then we combine all datasets into a centralized repository (e.g., Excel or CSV)\n\nStep 4: Clean data\n\nBy dropping columns with excessive missing values (e.g., 80%)\nUsing imputation methods to replace missing values\nRemoving duplicates and standardizing text formats\n\nStep 5: Analyze the Data\n\nWith our data in hand, we employ various analytical techniques to uncover insights and patterns, including:\n\nDescriptive statistics to summarize trends\nCorrelation analysis to identify relationships between factors\nSentiment analysis to understand customer emotions in reviews\n\nStep 6: Visualize the Findings\n\nWe communicate our findings through compelling visualizations, using:\n\nBar charts to illustrate complaints by product category\nLine graphs to track customer satisfaction over time\n\nStep 7: Communicate Insights and Recommendations\n\nFinally, we present a summary of our findings and provide actionable recommendations to stakeholders, using:\n\nPowerPoint or Google Slides presentations\nInteractive dashboards in Power BI or Tableau\nSummary reports in PDF or Word format, highlighting key takeaways\n\nA huge thank you to Esther Emoekpenefor their guidance.\nâ€¦more"
